Actually simpler: `shift(ofcolor(I, ONE), (0, -2))` shifts 1s left by 2. The intersection with original 1s gives... no that's not right.

Let me think again: For a middle cell at (r,c) to become 2, we need 1s at (r, c-1) and (r, c+1). So if I shift all 1s left by 1, I get positions right of 1s. If I shift all 1s right by 1, I get positions left of 1s. The intersection of these two shifted sets gives positions that have 1s on both sides - i.e., the middle positions!

So: `intersection(shift(ofcolor(I, ONE), LEFT), shift(ofcolor(I, ONE), RIGHT))` should give the middle cells.

Then I fill these with 2: `fill(I, TWO, that_intersection)`

